---
import Base from '@/layouts/Base.astro';
import TopNav from '@/components/TopNav.astro';

const siteUrl = (p: string) => new URL(p, Astro.site ?? 'https://mycelocity.com').href;

// AboutPage + Organization — tells Google who is behind the numbers.
const jsonLd = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'AboutPage',
  name: 'About Mycelocity',
  url: siteUrl('/about'),
  description:
    'The story behind Mycelocity — a free mushroom growing calculator built by a beginner grower who could not find a simple way to organize costs, yields and profit.',
  publisher: {
    '@type': 'Organization',
    name: 'Mycelocity',
    url: siteUrl('/'),
    logo: siteUrl('/logo.png'),
  },
};
---

<Base
  title="About Mycelocity — Why I Built a Free Mushroom Growing Calculator"
  description="The story behind Mycelocity: a free mushroom growing calculator I built as a beginner grower, after finding costs, yields and profit hard to organize. Built for other beginners too."
  jsonLd={jsonLd}
  path="/about"
>
  <TopNav />

  <main>
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 py-12 sm:px-6 lg:px-10 lg:py-16">
      <header class="mb-8">
        <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-stone-900 sm:text-4xl dark:text-stone-50">
          About Mycelocity
        </h1>
        <p class="mt-3 text-lg leading-relaxed text-stone-600 dark:text-stone-300">
          A free mushroom growing calculator, built by a beginner grower — for beginner growers.
        </p>
      </header>

      <div class="space-y-8 text-base leading-relaxed text-stone-600 dark:text-stone-300">
        <section>
          <h2 class="text-xl font-bold tracking-tight text-stone-900 dark:text-stone-50">
            How this started
          </h2>
          <p class="mt-3">
            I recently got into mushroom growing with a friend. We were looking for a fun way to make
            some money, and growing mushrooms hooked us almost immediately. Like most people, we
            started on YouTube — and I still remember one particularly good video on estimating the
            costs of starting a mushroom growing and selling operation.
          </p>
          <p class="mt-3">
            The problem was that once we tried to actually run the numbers ourselves, the costs,
            yields and everything in between were genuinely hard to organize and calculate. They all
            depend on each other — change your biological efficiency or your price per pound and the
            whole picture shifts — and juggling that across scattered notes and half-finished
            spreadsheets was a mess.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section>
          <h2 class="text-xl font-bold tracking-tight text-stone-900 dark:text-stone-50">
            So I built the tool I wanted
          </h2>
          <p class="mt-3">
            I'm into coding, so — armed with a new Claude Code subscription — I decided to build the
            calculator I wished we'd had, as a passion project. That became
            <a href="/calculators" class="text-accent-700 hover:underline dark:text-accent-300">the Mycelocity calculators</a>:
            a connected set of tools covering the main calculations for growing mushrooms as a
            business. They share one grow profile, so you change a value once and yield, cost, profit,
            break-even, capacity and ROI all update together — instead of recalculating everything by
            hand.
          </p>
          <p class="mt-3">
            Honestly, the tools here were enough for the two of us to get started as beginners and
            gave us solid estimates to plan around. I may keep adding calculators for more niche
            things over time, but the core is already what we actually used.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section>
          <h2 class="text-xl font-bold tracking-tight text-stone-900 dark:text-stone-50">
            How the numbers work
          </h2>
          <p class="mt-3">
            Nothing here is a black box. Each calculator shows the exact formula it uses, drawn from
            standard cultivation metrics — biological efficiency measured against <em>dry</em>
            substrate weight — and basic unit economics like cost of goods, contribution margin,
            break-even and payback. The default values are sensible starting points based on common
            species (oyster, shiitake, lion's mane, king oyster) and typical small setups. They're
            meant to be replaced with your own measured numbers as soon as you have a few flushes
            logged. The
            <a href="/guides" class="text-accent-700 hover:underline dark:text-accent-300">guides</a>
            explain the reasoning behind each one.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section>
          <h2 class="text-xl font-bold tracking-tight text-stone-900 dark:text-stone-50">
            Who it's for
          </h2>
          <p class="mt-3">
            People in the same spot we were: curious beginners sizing up a first grow, and hobbyists
            wondering whether mushrooms could actually make money. It's completely free, with no
            sign-up — if a default looks off or you spot something that could be clearer, I'd genuinely
            like to know.
          </p>
        </section>
      </div>

      <div class="mt-10 flex flex-wrap gap-3">
        <a
          href="/calculators"
          class="inline-flex items-center rounded-lg bg-chanterelle-500 px-5 py-2.5 text-sm font-semibold text-white transition-colors hover:bg-chanterelle-600"
        >
          Open the calculators
        </a>
        <a
          href="/guides"
          class="inline-flex items-center rounded-lg border border-stone-300 bg-paper px-5 py-2.5 text-sm font-semibold text-stone-700 hover:border-accent-400 hover:text-accent-700 dark:border-stone-700 dark:bg-stone-900 dark:text-stone-200 dark:hover:border-accent-500"
        >
          Read the guides
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </main>
</Base>
